## Q3. Linux Shell Commands

  1. Make the MIMIC v2.2 data available at location ~/mimic.

Refer to the documentation https://physionet.org/content/mimiciv/2.2/ for details of data files. Please, do not put these data files into Git; they are big. Do not copy them into your directory. Do not decompress the gz data files. These create unnecessary big files and are not big-data-friendly practices. Read from the data folder ~/mimic directly in following exercises.

Use Bash commands to answer following questions. Answer I created a symbolic link âmimicâ to my mimic data folder. The symbolic link is located in my home directory. The symbolic link is created using the following command: ln -s ~/mimic/ ~/mimic. The following command is used to check the symbolic link: ls -l ~/mimic/. The output of the command is shown below.

ls -l ~/mimic/
  1. Display the contents in the folders hosp and icu using Bash command ls -l. Why are these data files distributed as .csv.gz files instead of .csv (comma separated values) files? Read the page https://mimic.mit.edu/docs/iv/ to understand whatâs in each folder.
ls -l ~/mimic/hosp
ls -l ~/mimic/icu

AnswerThe reason the data files are distributed as .csv.gz files instead of just .csv files is to compress the data and reduce the file size. The .gz extension indicates that the files are compressed using gzip compression. By compressing the files, it not only saves storage space but also makes it faster to transfer and download the files. The hosp folder contains hospital-level data, including information about the hospitals in the MIMIC-IV dataset. The icu folder contains intensive care unit (ICU)-level data, including information about the ICUs and the patients admitted to those ICUs.

  1. Briefly describe what Bash commands zcat, zless, zmore, and zgrep do. Answer The âzcatâ command is used to display the contents of a compressed file. The âzlessâ command is used to display the contents of a compressed file one page at a time. The âzmoreâ command is used to diaplay the contents of a compressed file one screen at a time. The âzgrepâ command is used to search for a pattern in a compressed file.

  2. (Looping in Bash) Whatâs the output of the following bash script?

for datafile in ~/mimic/hosp/{a,l,pa}*.gz
do
  ls -l $datafile
done

Answer The output of the bash script is the list of files in the âhospâ folder that start with âaâ, âlâ, or âpaâ and end with â.gzâ.

Display the number of lines in each data file using a similar loop. (Hint: combine linux commands zcat < and wc -l.)

for datafile in ~/mimic/hosp/{a,l,pa}*.gz
do
   echo "Number of lines in $datafile: $(zcat < $datafile | wc -l)"
done
  1. Display the first few lines of admissions.csv.gz. How many rows are in this data file? How many unique patients (identified by subject_id) are in this data file? Do they match the number of patients listed in the patients.csv.gz file? (Hint: combine Linux commands zcat <, head/tail, awk, sort, uniq, wc, and so on.)
zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | head -5
zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | wc -l
zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | awk -F, '{print $1}' | sort | uniq | wc -l
zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/patients.csv.gz | wc -l

Answer The first few lines of the âadmissions.csv.gzâ file are displayed using the following command: zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | head -5. The number of rows in the âadmissions.csv.gzâ file is displayed using the following command: zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | wc -l, there are 431232 rows. The number of unique patients in the âadmissions.csv.gzâ file is displayed using the following command: zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/admissions.csv.gz | awk -F, '{print $1}' | sort | uniq | wc -l, there are 180734 patients. The number of patients listed in the âpatients.csv.gzâ file is displayed using the following command: zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/patients.csv.gz | wc -l, there are 299713 patients. The number of unique patients in the âadmissions.csv.gzâ file does not matche the number of patients listed in the âpatients.csv.gzâ file.

Q4. Whoâs popular in Price and Prejudice

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.
wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt

Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git. Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo $char:
  # some bash commands here
done
  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt
  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?
